05812nam a22007455i 9780292771574DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211981txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927715747 a10.7560/7301752doi  a(DE-B1597)587405  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04aThe House at Work /ced. by G. Calvin Mackenzie, Joseph Cooper. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1981  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tCoping in a Complex Age: Challenge, Response, and Reform in the House of Representatives -- tPart I. Defining the Job -- tThe Context of Job Performance -- tIntroduction -- t1. Can Congress Ever Be a Popular Institution? -- t2. The Two Arenas of Congress -- t3. Casework in the House -- t4. The Politics of Congressional Ethics -- tPart II. Managing the Work -- tThe Context of Work Management -- tIntroduction -- t5. Controlling Legislative Time -- t6. Personnel Management in the House -- t7. The Management of Legislative Offices -- t8. Providing Administrative Support Services to the House -- tPart III. Informing the Decision-Making Process -- tThe Context of Information and Decision Making -- tIntroduction -- t9. Congressional Information Sources -- t10. Computer Usage in the House -- t11. The Evolving Role and Effectiveness of the Congressional Research Agencies -- tConclusion -- tOrganization and Innovation in the House of Representatives -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere exists a rich literature on the workings of the United States Congress, but The House at Work is the first book to focus on the institutional performance of the House of Representatives. A complete overview of the complex functioning and dynamics of Congress is presented by distinguished contributors, drawing upon both real-life experience and organization theory. Each essay presents material on activities central to legislative work in the House, including the internal operations of member and committee offices, the administrative support system of the House, the impact of organizational structure and information resources on individual decision making, the expanding application of computer technology, the character of the personnel system, and the processing of constituent casework. Nearly all contributors were professional staff members of the U.S. House Commission on Administrative Review in 1976 and 1977, whose analysis of the internal operations of the House was acomprehensive investigation. Their academic training, buttressed by significant practical experience on Capitol Hill, makes this book of great value to both students and scholars of the legislative process. In addition to the editors, the contributors include Glenn R. Parker, Thomas E. Cavanagh, Allan J. Katz, John R. Johannes, Thomas J. O'Donnell, David W. Brady, Louis Sandy Maisel, Susan Webb Hammond, Jarold A. Kieffer, James A. Thurber, and Jeffrey A. Goldberg.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBrady, David W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavanagh, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Joseph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Jeffrey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Susan Webb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohannes, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators